1. Getting Started: Fetching the Test File

Before writing the script, fetch a live copy of the page so you have something to test against locally. Run this on your command line:
Bash

wget -q -O thepage.htm https://stockanalysis.com/stocks/goog/

(Open thepage.htm in a text editor or use grep to quickly verify it contains the stock price and the text-4xl font-bold class).
2. The Einstein Lab Script (getprice6.sh)

Create your script: nano getprice6.sh

Here is the complete script built exactly to your recipe. By chaining the commands with pipes (|) and spreading them across multiple lines using the backslash (\), the code remains highly readable.
Bash

#!/bin/bash

cat thepage.htm | \
tr -d '\r' | \
tr -d '\n' | \
sed -e 's/<div/\n<div/g' | \
sed -e 's/<\/div>/<\/div>\n/g' | \
grep "text-4xl font-bold" | \
sed -e 's/<\/div>//g' | \
sed -e 's/^.*>//g'

How the Recipe Works:

    tr -d '\r': Deletes all carriage returns (Windows EOL characters).

    tr -d '\n': Deletes all standard newlines, crushing the entire HTML file into one massive, unbroken line.

    sed -e 's/<div/\n<div/g': Injects a newline right before every <div tag starts.

    sed -e 's/<\/div>/<\/div>\n/g': Injects a newline right after every </div> tag ends. (At this point, every div block is neatly isolated on its own line).

    grep "text-4xl font-bold": Throws away all lines except the one containing the specific class for the stock price.

    sed -e 's/<\/div>//g': Strips the closing </div> tag off the end of our isolated line.

    sed -e 's/^.*>//g': The regular expression ^.*> means "Start at the beginning of the line (^), match any number of characters (.*), all the way up to the last closing bracket (>)". By replacing all of that with nothing, it strips away the opening <div class="..."> tag, leaving only the pure number.

Make it executable and test:
Bash

chmod +x getprice6.sh
./getprice6.sh

(If it outputs just the number, e.g., 156.47, you are ready to upload to Einstein).
3. Afterwards: The Real-World Script (getprice)

Once you have your marks, you can modify the script for real-world use. This version drops the requirement for a temporary file, fetches the page silently on the fly, and accepts any stock ticker as an argument.

Create a file named getprice in your $HOME/bin directory:
Bash

#!/bin/bash

# Check if a stock ticker was provided
if [ -z "$1" ]; then
    echo "Usage: getprice <ticker> (e.g., getprice msft)"
    exit 1
fi

# Fetch the URL directly into the pipeline
wget -q -O - "https://stockanalysis.com/stocks/$1/" | \
tr -d '\r' | \
tr -d '\n' | \
sed -e 's/<div/\n<div/g' | \
sed -e 's/<\/div>/<\/div>\n/g' | \
grep "text-4xl font-bold" | \
sed -e 's/<\/div>//g' | \
sed -e 's/^.*>//g'
